'''Kit and Caboodle''' is slang and is somewhat redundant in that "kit" and "caboodle" are essentially the same thing; collections of things.

According to the [http://www.OED.com/ Oxford English Dictionary], the "kit" portion of the saying derives from the Middle Dutch word, "kitte." (A kitte is a wooden vessel generally made of hooped staves; a stave being a narrow strip of word or iron plates which - lined up edge to edge - formed the sides of the vessel.)

Caboodle appears to be derived from the antiquaited word "boodle" which meant essentially the same thing as the word kit. Though the QPD Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins defines "caboodle" as more along the lines of "the whole lot," with boodle meaning a "pile of money." Which in turn is derived from the Dutch word "boedal," meaning property.

At some point, this phrase turned into kit and caboodle simply to add the "k" sound prior to boodle as Americans just prefer a balanced alliteration in such speech.

So the entire expression is essentially derived from the Dutch. The OED2 has sited the word kit from 1785 and caboodle more recently in 1848 with the original boedal showing up ealier in 1833. But also with a 1699 usage meaning an estate of a dead man as well as a 1827 reference to the more modern spelling boodle in 1827, this time referring to "a crowd."